  <article><div class="timeline-marker"><span>01</span><small>1976 onward</small></div><div><h2>A food-loving childhood</h2><p>Born into a Marwari family where food was central to daily life, Gautam grew up without much food discipline. Sweets, bread, cheese and eggs were favourites, and overeating became normal. Dental problems appeared early, followed later by recurring digestive discomfort.</p></div></article>
  <article><div class="timeline-marker"><span>02</span><small>Around age 25</small></div><div><h2>When health demanded attention</h2><p>By his mid-twenties, bleeding gums, constipation and severe piles made it impossible to ignore the effects of his lifestyle. A stay at a nature cure hospital became the turning point that changed the direction of his life.</p></div></article>
  <article><div class="timeline-marker"><span>03</span><small>The turning point</small></div><div><h2>Meeting his guru</h2><p>At the hospital, Gautam met the teacher who would shape his understanding of naturopathy. What began as treatment became a philosophy: naturopathy was not simply about responding to disease, but learning an art of living that protects health.</p></div></article>
  <article><div class="timeline-marker"><span>04</span><small>Two decades</small></div><div><h2>Learning discipline slowly</h2><p>The ideas were simple, but living them consistently was not easy. Over nearly two decades, Gautam learned, experimented, unlearned old habits and steadily rebuilt his relationship with food, fasting, rest and daily rhythm.</p></div></article>
